<paragraph blockId="1.[151,746,1422,1449]" box="[151,746,1422,1449]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,746,1422,1449]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,746,1422,1449]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
Key to Argentinian species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Casal" authorityYear="1964" box="[524,648,1422,1449]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Limaytilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[524,648,1422,1449]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Limaytilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(males)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="584" type="key">
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,168,1491,1512]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">1.</emphasis>
Specimen large, body shape robust (12.0– 
<quantity box="[632,721,1491,1513]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5699999999999998" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" unit="mm" value="15.7">15.7 mm</quantity>
.) (Figs 3, 4) or slender (
<quantity box="[954,1098,1491,1513]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.33" metricValueMax="1.54" metricValueMin="1.1199999999999999" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" unit="mm" value="13.3" valueMax="15.4" valueMin="11.2">11.2–15.4 mm</quantity>
; rarely a little more than 10.0 mm) (Figs 1, 2); head quadrangular in dorsal view with outline of the posterior margin of the head slightly convex to virtually straight (Figs 14, 15, 18, 19)................................................................................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,1436,1549,1570]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">2</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,159,1579,1600]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">-</emphasis>
Specimen small to medium and body shape slender (5.0–10.0 mm) (Figs 5–10); head triangular in dorsal view with outline of the posterior margin of the head strongly convex (Fig. 11)......................................................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,1436,1608,1629]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">3</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,167,1637,1658]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">2.</emphasis>
Specimens slender (Figs 1, 2); mandible robust and strongly delineated (Figs 14, 16); basal ventral tooth of mandible attached to a keel thus appearing bilobate (Fig. 16, indicated); first segment of metasoma relatively long (2.3× as long as broad) (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 20–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1902,1927]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,217,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,217,1852]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 20–29. Limaytilla spp. ♂. 20, L. diaguita sp. nov., first metasomal segment (dorsal). 21, L. huarpe, first metasomal segment (dorsal). 22–24, L. diaguita: 22, genitalia; 23, paramere (apical); 24, gonobase (side). 25–27, L. huarpe: 25, genitalia; 26, paramere (apical); 27, gonobase (side). 28, 29, L. orlandoi: 28, habitus (lateral); 29, habitus (dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3227932/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
); antennal projected as a cone-shaped protuberance well developed (Fig. 18)...................... 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1251,1436,1696,1718]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<taxonomicName authority="Torréns &amp; Fidalgo, 2019" authorityName="Torréns &amp; Fidalgo" authorityYear="2019" box="[1251,1359,1696,1718]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Limaytilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diaguita" status="sp. nov">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1251,1359,1696,1718]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">L. diaguita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1365,1436,1696,1717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" rank="species">sp. nov</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,159,1726,1747]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">-</emphasis>
Specimens robust (Figs 3, 4); mandible not robust and barely delineated (Figs 15, 17); basal ventral tooth simple (Fig. 17, indicated); first segment of metasoma relatively short (1.4× as long as broad) (
<figureCitation box="[983,1055,1755,1777]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–29" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1902,1927]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,217,1852]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,217,1852]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 20–29. Limaytilla spp. ♂. 20, L. diaguita sp. nov., first metasomal segment (dorsal). 21, L. huarpe, first metasomal segment (dorsal). 22–24, L. diaguita: 22, genitalia; 23, paramere (apical); 24, gonobase (side). 25–27, L. huarpe: 25, genitalia; 26, paramere (apical); 27, gonobase (side). 28, 29, L. orlandoi: 28, habitus (lateral); 29, habitus (dorsal)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3227932/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
); antennal tubercle projected as a slight sub-triangular protuberance (flattened laterally) (Fig. 19).......................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Casal" authorityName="Casal" box="[1276,1436,1784,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Limaytilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huarpe">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1276,1436,1784,1806]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1276,1373,1784,1806]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">L. huarpe</emphasis>
Casal
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,167,1813,1834]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">3.</emphasis>
Mandible widened abruptly on anterodorsal margin, widening to the height of the first dorsal tooth and tapering towards the apex (Fig. 12)....................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Cambra, Quintero &amp; Pagliano" authorityName="Cambra, Quintero &amp; Pagliano" box="[1029,1436,1843,1865]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Limaytilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="larioja">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1029,1436,1843,1865]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1029,1120,1843,1865]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">L. larioja</emphasis>
Cambra, Quintero &amp; Pagliano
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" box="[151,1436,1872,1894]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1872,1894]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,159,1872,1893]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">-</emphasis>
Mandible with almost parallel margins from base to apex (Fig. 13).............................................. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1424,1436,1872,1893]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">4</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,163,1901,1922]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">4</emphasis>
Antennal tubercles with sharp projections and converging ventrally (see Fig. 
<quantity box="[954,990,1901,1923]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Casal, O. H." box="[994,1110,1901,1923]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" pagination="81 - 103" refId="ref6819" refString="Casal, O. H. (1964) Revision de Lymaitilla. Nuevo genero endemico y nocturno de Sphaeropthalmini (Hymenoptera, Mutillidae). Acta Zoologica Lilloana, 20, 81 - 103." type="journal article" year="1964">Casal, 1964</bibRefCitation>
); vertex and frons foveo-reticulate (see Fig. 
<quantity box="[315,352,1931,1953]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Casal, O. H." box="[357,472,1931,1953]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" pagination="81 - 103" refId="ref6819" refString="Casal, O. H. (1964) Revision de Lymaitilla. Nuevo genero endemico y nocturno de Sphaeropthalmini (Hymenoptera, Mutillidae). Acta Zoologica Lilloana, 20, 81 - 103." type="journal article" year="1964">Casal, 1964</bibRefCitation>
)............................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Casal" authorityName="Casal" box="[1238,1436,1931,1953]" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Limaytilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pehuenche">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1238,1436,1931,1953]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1238,1373,1931,1953]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">L. pehuenche</emphasis>
Casal
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1491,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<keyLead pageId="1" pageNumber="584">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,159,1960,1981]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584">-</emphasis>
Antennal tubercles with inner subtriangular and dorsally convergent projection (see Fig. 
<quantity box="[1066,1102,1960,1982]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Casal, O. H." box="[1107,1223,1960,1982]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" pagination="81 - 103" refId="ref6819" refString="Casal, O. H. (1964) Revision de Lymaitilla. Nuevo genero endemico y nocturno de Sphaeropthalmini (Hymenoptera, Mutillidae). Acta Zoologica Lilloana, 20, 81 - 103." type="journal article" year="1964">Casal, 1964</bibRefCitation>
); vertex and frons with medium-sized contiguous punctures (see Fig. 
<quantity box="[667,704,1989,2011]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Casal, O. H." box="[710,824,1989,2011]" pageId="1" pageNumber="584" pagination="81 - 103" refId="ref6819" refString="Casal, O. H. (1964) Revision de Lymaitilla. Nuevo genero endemico y nocturno de Sphaeropthalmini (Hymenoptera, Mutillidae). Acta Zoologica Lilloana, 20, 81 - 103." type="journal article" year="1964">Casal, 1964</bibRefCitation>
)..................................... 
